observations.recommendation:
We recommended to the management to:
Require the Municipal Accountant to immediately prepare Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) to adjust the overstated inventory accounts balances as of year-end and submit the same to this audit team for our review and evaluation;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to henceforth record the receipt of drugs, medicines, and medical supplies using the perpetual inventory method and the subsequent issuance of the same based on the SSMI to record the corresponding expense account pursuant to Sections 114 and 121, Volume 1 of NGAS Manual;
Instruct the Municipal Health Officer and/or the General Services Officer to prepare weekly SSMI as the correct basis of the Municipal Accountant to record inventory issuances; and
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct semi-annual physical inventory counts and prepare a Report of the Physical Count of Inventories (RPCI). This report must be submitted to the MAccO, GSO, and MHO to reconcile their respective records. Submit the same to the audit team by July 31 of the current year and January 31 of the following year for the first and second semesters, respectively.

We recommended to the management to:
Submit immediately a letter from the DILG Regional Director explicitly approving the foreign travel of the selected officials and employees to South Korea, including the other lacking relevant documentary requirements, to the Office of the Auditor. Otherwise, refund the total disbursed amount totaling ₱1.696 million;
Ensure that “lakbay aral” activities meet the conditions required by DILG-DBM JMC No. 2 dated September 23, 2016. Remind the Municipal Planning and Development Officer and all approving signatories of Disbursement Voucher to ensure that benchmarking activities are specifically defined or disclosed in the LGU’s CapDev program, ensuring such activities are responsive to the capacity development of participants;
Refrain from conducting “lakbay aral” activities abroad which can be addressed by a more economical mode of CapDev intervention that can be undertaken locally; and,
Submit written valid justification for the necessity of each official and department head's participation to the benchmarking activity in South Korea.

We recommended to the management to perform the following:

1)Require the newly reconstituted Inventory and Disposal Committees to hasten the inspection, appraisal and disposal of those identified unserviceable heavy equipment and other motor vehicles owned by the LGU-Talakag, strictly adhering with the disposal procedures of the above-mentioned applicable rules and regulations;

2)Submit immediately to the audit team for auditorial review the complete documentary requirements prior review and inspection by the COA Regional Office No. 10’s Regional Technical Audit Group (RTAG);

3)Resort to proper disposition thru public auction or to other mode of disposal, if deemed appropriate, subject to applicable rules and regulations;

4)Require the Municipal Accountant to drop from the books of accounts those properties already disposed thru a drawing of Journal Entry Voucher, to be substantiated with complete documentation subject for post-audit; and,

5)Treat any proceeds from sale of unserviceable properties as a general income under the General Fund subject for supplemental appropriation to finance priority programs and projects of the municipality.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation to the management to:

1.Create internal guidelines/policies relating to communication expenses by defining a ceiling/limit for the amount, the number of accounts, the eligible/entitled personnel, the availment options and the corresponding documentary requirements for such reimbursement;

2.Obligate reimbursable communication expenses under its appropriate expense line item instead of erroneously charging it against office supplies, unless otherwise justified;

3.Stop the practice of purchasing cell cards that did not undergo the proper procurement procedures; and,

4.Strictly ensure that succeeding disbursements relating to communication expenses are complete with supporting documents.

We recommended to the management to perform the following:
1.) Require the HRM Officer to strictly impose that, prior the rendition of actual service, a job order worker should effect his/her full signature on the job order contract;

2) Adhere strictly with the provisions of CSC-COA-DBM JC No. 1, s. 2017, and COA-DBM JC No. 2, s. 2020, on the conditions, limitations, and payment of daily wage for hired JO workers;

3) Assess the functions and the existing organizational structure and staffing pattern of the LGU-Talakag. Evaluate the necessity of hiring job order workers, taking into account the possible elimination of duplicated and/or unnecessary tasks and functions;

4) Observe the proper approving authority on job order contracts unless there is an ordinance specifically authorizing the Vice Mayor to hire them;

5) Create an internal policy or guideline on the hiring of job order workers, including the remuneration, attendance and disciplinary measures.

