We recommended to the management to:

1. Stop the practice of drawing check in favor to the league/association instead to each personnel to establish accountability over such disbursed amount;

2. Record to “Advances to Officers and Employees” account all registration fees paid in advance subject to liquidation.

We recommended to the management to do the following:
1. Submit the lacking documentary requirements and valid justification for those transactions noted with deficiencies;
2. Submit the bills (stating the rate per day, number of guests and name of guest/s per room) and the necessary certifications of the Local Chief Executive (LCE) or his authorized representative as absolutely necessary in the performance of an assignment;
3. Ensure, henceforth, that proper supporting documents for cash advances and their subsequent liquidations are attached;
4. Assure that the name of the specific person to be granted with cash advance is already identified prior such grant;
5. Submit justification for the excessive hotel claims of the identified four participants; Otherwise, effect refund of the same totaling ₱7,200.00.

We recommended to the management to do the following:

1. Submit a valid justification and legal basis on the claim for the lodging/accommodation at the rate of P1,800 per day per participant instead of the allowable rate of P900 only; 
2. Submit the bills (stating the rate per day, number of guests and name of guest/s per room) and the necessary certifications of the Local Chief Executive (LCE) or his authorized representative as absolutely necessary in the performance of an assignment;
3. Stop the practice of granting cash advances for travels more than the allowed accommodation rate per EO 77; 
4. Stop the practice of signing documents on behalf of the LCE without printing the name and position/designation of his representative and without attaching authority to do so; 
5. Refrain from tampering/changing the names of recipients on the payroll without bearing the signature of the proper official to confirm such change; and
6. Submit explanation/justification on the tampering/changing of names of participants and the discrepancies of the dates in the itinerary of travel versus actual dates of travel.

 Further, required the Municipal Accountant to immediately submit to the audit team the above-mentioned lacking documentary requirements. Prospectively, ensure that disbursements are supported with complete documentation as required by COA Circular No. 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012 and in accordance with EO 77.

We recommended to the management to do the following:

1. Conduct a feasibility study and assess the sustainability of the Local Economic Enterprises;
2. Maintain separate books for LEEs as noted in the NGAS Manual for transactions relating to the operations of the LEEs;
3. Ensure the preparation of Annual Operating Budgets for LEEs using its respective estimated/projected income relating to its operations; and
4. Appoint full-time managers for each LEE in line with existing guidelines.

Otherwise, if in case the LGU determines that the LEEs are no longer feasible, we recommend that the LGU should absorb the enterprises, particularly the Public Market & Slaughterhouse Operations and the Heavy Equipment Unit, in the general fund under a certain office/department as among its priority services and not as local economic enterprises.

We recommended to the management to submit the following lacking documents to facilitate post-audit of accounts:

1. Basis for the rates of the meal and fare allowances;

2. Liquidation or Justification for the Variance;

3. Certified list of volunteers, frontliners, medical practioners, and vaccinees;

4. Justification for the deleted names and additional fare allowances to selective individuals in the payrolls;

5. Vaccination Plan; and

6. Authorization Letters for those received via proxy.

Thereafter, ensure that the documentation of all claims is complete and orderly (i.e. pagination, item number, and etc.) with correct information.

