1. Basis for the rates of the meal and fare allowances;
2. Liquidation or Justification for the Variance;
3. Certified list of volunteers, frontliners, medical practioners, and vaccinees;
4. Justification for the deleted names and additional fare allowances to selective individuals in the payrolls;
5. Vaccination Plan; and
6. Authorization Letters for those received via proxy.

Thereafter, ensure that the documentation of all claims is complete and orderly (i.e. pagination, item number, and etc.) with correct information.

We recommended to the management to justify the deficiencies noted and to submit all of the following documents to facilitate post-audit of the distribution of relief goods in order to avoid the issuance of Notice of Suspension:

1. Distribution sheets with signed acknowledgment of recipients of goods;
2. Approved lists of targeted beneficiaries;
3. Authorization letters, in case of receipts via proxy, if any;
4. Waivers of target recipients who refused the goods voluntarily, if any;
5. Approved lists of replacements, if any;
6. Summary of relief goods distribution per barangay, if any; and
7. Copy of the guidelines for the welfare goods distribution process of the LGU, if any.

Further, we recommended to the management to conduct physical inventory of the remaining welfare goods for distribution in order to establish the validity of the amount reflected under the account “Welfare Goods Inventory for Distribution” in the Statement of Financial Position as of the end of December 31, 2020.

Furthermore, we recommended to the Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjusting entries for the difference between the actual physical inventory of the remaining welfare goods versus the balance reflected in the books of accounts of the agency.

We recommended to require the key players of the shelter program including those other functionaries created for the purpose must have to come up with some more cohesive efforts, strategies and set up appropriate project phasing to materialize that noble intention of the municipality by taking into consideration and prioritize the following:

1.Allocation of funds for the acquisition of remaining land areas;

2.Endeavor to have those acquired land for shelter program to be reclassified into a residential use in a manner and procedures required by law. 

3.Secure approval of development plan from regulatory body and allocate appropriate fund for processing fees and for other related payments;

4.Allocate funds and implement any infrastructures facilities necessary within projected period. 5.Establish effective monitoring procedures to ensures putting the implementation of the project at its right course.

We recommended that the Municipal Management the following:

1) Conduct retrieval proceeding for those equipments and other properties that were in the custody of the above-referred to former officials and personnel of the Municipality;

2) Re-issue those retrieved properties that are found to be significant in the Agency’s operation to interested/authorized end-users;

3) Cancel those AREs for those equipment and other properties that are actually not in the possession of those retired/resigned/terminated/transferred/deceased former official and personnel of the Municipality no longer in service and accordingly issue new ARE to the actual custodian/current end-user to herein referred properties

4) Impose the periodic renewal of ARE as required by the regulation; and endeavor to apply for relief of accountability for those equipment and other properties that were legitimately omitted or separated from possession and can no longer be found no on occasion by fault or negligence. 5)Otherwise, institute appropriate action for those unjustified unaccounted properties previously issued to officials and personnel no longer in service with the Municipality.

